\f0\i\b\fs24 \cf2 Dashboard\
\b0 This will include the ability to create new Elements & Metadata Templates, as well as run Metadata Templates. We will also include the ability to see recently created and run items.\ \
\b Element Builder\
\b0 Create elements for use in the Metadata Template Builder here. Choosing \'91Done\'92 saves the element and brings the user back to the Dashboard.\ \
\b Metadata Template Creator\
\b0 Here you add Elements to create a template. Ideally, the system will autosave the form as you are creating it (after each element is added, the form is saved, eliminating the risk that work could be lost). Choosing \'91Done\'92 will bring the user back to the Dashboard.\ \
\b Metadata Template Runtime\
\b0 This is where a user runs the Metadata Templates they have created. We will include a list of all their templates (up for discussion on this), that would allow them to run an unlimited amount of templates consecutively. Choosing \'91Done\'92 will return the user to the dashboard.\ \
\b Infinite Runtime\
\b0 This simply symbolizes that a user could run an unlimited amount of runtimes without returning to the Dashboard.}

\f0\i\b\fs24 \cf2 Navigation\
\b0 We are proposing a modern, mobile ready navigation structure for the new site. Users click on the home icon to go to the home page from anywhere on the site. They click on the menu icon (often lovingly called the \'91hamburger menu\'92) to open up the navigation menu. Search is available here as well. \ \ This navigation system revolutionizes the current system where pages are frequently buried 6-7 clicks deep, in menus that are in multiple confusing places on each page. \ \ This menu makes nearly all sections and pages of the site accessible from one navigation structure throughout the entire site, which makes a much more consistent browsing environment. \ \ This system is also extremely friendly to mobile devices. It is designed to be responsive all the way down to small screen sizes of smartphones, while maintaining the same consistent methods of navigating. It takes the lessons learned from the creation of our mobile friendly templates last year and significantly refines it. \ \
\b Features\
\b0 In an effort to cut down on the cognitive load of the current circle graphic on the home page - which hides up to 32 pieces of content within the circles - we have limited the features on the home page to 10. Users will be able to see all of them in these thumbnails. Each feature will show for 3 seconds and will then go to the next one. These thumbnails are tied to annotation 4, the feature image. Clicking on a feature pauses auto-play and users can then manually click any feature they are interested in and look at it for as long as they wish.\ \
\b Logo\
\b0 This will be placed over the featured item to give the site added depth. Clicking on the logo anywhere in the site brings you back to home.\ \
\b Feature\
\b0 Large background images with text on top. We are intentionally keeping this block vague in the wireframes as we have some interesting creative direction that will be shown during concept designs. \ \
\b Home Page Text Block\
\b0 We need an area on the home page that briefly tells the story of Saint Mary\'92s. This is both for our prospective student and parent personas to get a good first reaction, as well as for good search engine optimization.\ \
\b Persona Calls to Action\
\b0 Here we take five of our personas and cater content and calls to action (CTA) to them. All five will initially be the same size with a title on top of a background image. Rolling over them expands the box, showing a short blurb to entice that persona to go deeper. We\'92ve shown that animation in the second block where Prospective Graduate Students is expanded.\ \ This block will help bring our different audiences into the site funnel in the way we deem optimal.\ \
\b Persona Personalized Content\
\b0 If we have a persona identified, such as a prospective undergrad who has visited other admissions pages previously and has a cookie as a result, we can open the bottom bar item for prospective undergrads and load a feature that we\'92ve identified as of interest to prospective undergrads. \ \
\b Expanded Navigation Menu\
\b0 Here we see the first level of the expanded navigation menu. It includes user interface elements to close the menu, and subnav items. \ \
\b Navigation Items\
\b0 Click on these first level nav items to get to the 2nd level menu. Arrow icons show that this will slide in a new menu. Note that a user can open the landing page \'91Academics\'92 by clicking a 2nd time on the text area of that button.\ \
\b Lower Priority Navigation\
\b0 These items don\'92t get as many visits, but are still necessary to have access to. They will be designed to take a lower priority than main navigation.\ \
\b S0cial Sharing\
\b0 We are proposing that we build a new social sharing page that this graphic will link to. It\'92s important to have a social presence that is easily accessed, but we also don\'92t want to immediately take people off the site and onto social networks where they can easily be distracted.\ \
\b Second Level Navigation\
\b0 Here we start to see the beauty, as well as the simplicity of this navigation structure. Fly out menus appear on click and the user can see the entire content collection for each section. Here we are showing what would happen if Academics was clicked. \ \
\b Third Level Navigation\
\b0 We use the plus sign to identify embedded third level content in the menu. Plus signs open accordion style drawers that house page links. Note that a user can open the landing page \'91Core Curriculum Course Offerings\'92 by clicking a 2nd time on the text area of that button.\ \
\b Fourth (and more) Level Navigation\
\b0 We strongly suggest staying at a maximum of three levels of navigation. Anymore than that gets tedious and confusing for users. That said, we realize that there is quite a bit of content on the current site that requires four levels of depth, and sometimes more. \ \ Here we are showing \'91Browser All Departments\'92 as an example. Clicking that button brings up the menu, which scrolls up and down showing all departments. The UI changes to an X on the button to close that panel. \ \ The far right panel can also include additional navigation buttons. Clicking those will overlay menus with an X out controller to close them. This allows 5, 6, 7, etc. levels of navigation menu depth. Please use with caution, we are designing the menu to allow this, but a design constraint of 3 levels, 4 absolute max should be adhered to to keep your users sanity in check. \ \
\b Mobile Menu Icon\
\b0 Smartphones have less space and we will accommodate this by showing only the \'91hamburger menu\'92. The menu will work the same as shown in the desktop mockups, which is a huge benefit of this design.\ \
\b Mobile Layouts\
\b0 Smartphone layouts will layout differently than desktop. We are designing all page elements to elegantly stack on top of each other as screen sizes diminish. \ \
\b Mobile Menu Layouts\
\b0 The next few screens show how the menu works on a smartphone. Note that all menu levels overlay, and we will enable gesture swiping to move backward in the stack.}
